
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `mkfontdir` yek file `fonts.dir` misazad. In file index-e font-ha dar yek pooshe (directory) ra zakhire mikonad. Vaghti ke yek server X font-ha ra load mikonad, az in file baraye peida kardan font-ha be soorat sari' estefade mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `mkfontdir -v`  --> 📢  Namayesh etela'at bishtar dar morede font-ha va amaleye sakhtan file `fonts.dir`.
    🔹 `mkfontdir -e <esme_programe>` --> ✏️  Ezafe kardane yek dastoor baraye dorost kardan scale font-ha.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ mkfontdir

    🔹 Dar poosheye فعلی, file `fonts.dir` ra misazad.

    $ mkfontdir /usr/share/fonts/truetype

    🔹 Dar poosheye `/usr/share/fonts/truetype`, file `fonts.dir` ra misazad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ mkfontdir

    🔹 Agar font-haye jadidi dar poosheye فعلی ezafe shode bashand, in dastoor file `fonts.dir` ra dobare misazad ta server X betavand font-haye jadid ra be dorosti peida konad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `mkfontdir` command creates a `fonts.dir` file. This file stores an index of the fonts in a directory. When an X server loads fonts, it uses this file to quickly locate them.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `mkfontdir -v`  --> 📢  Display more verbose information about the fonts and the process of creating the `fonts.dir` file.
    🔹 `mkfontdir -e <program_name>` --> ✏️  Add a command for creating scaled fonts.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ mkfontdir

    🔹 Creates a `fonts.dir` file in the current directory.

    $ mkfontdir /usr/share/fonts/truetype

    🔹 Creates a `fonts.dir` file in the `/usr/share/fonts/truetype` directory.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ mkfontdir

    🔹 If new fonts have been added to the current directory, this command recreates the `fonts.dir` file so the X server can properly find the new fonts.
